.TH DT 1 "2026" "The-JLC-Project" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
dt \- print the current date and time
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B dt
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B dt
prints the current local date and time in the format:
.PP
.RS
YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS
.RE
.PP
It reads the system clock via
.BR time (2)
and
.BR localtime (3),
then formats the result with a single
.BR printf (3)
call.
There are no flags or arguments.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Always exits 0.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Print the current timestamp:
.B dt
.PP
Output example:
.EX
2026-03-21 15:04:05
.EE
.TP
Capture in a variable (sh):
.EX
NOW=$(dt)
echo "Started at $NOW"
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR date (1)
.SH AUTHORS
The-JLC-Project contributors.
